President Obama has appointed Rashad Hussain as his Special Envoy to the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC), which is the second largest inter-governmental organization in the world. In this role, Hussain will strengthen and expand partnerships between the United States and Muslims worldwide. President Obama praised Hussain's accomplishments as a lawyer and his contributions to developing partnerships outlined in Obama's Cairo speech. Hussain is currently Deputy Associate Counsel to President Obama, focusing on national security, new media, and science and technology issues. He has also worked with the National Security Staff in pursuing the "New Beginning" outlined in Obama's 2009 address in Cairo. Hussain's previous experience includes working as a Trial Attorney at the U.S. Department of Justice and as a legislative assistant on the House Judiciary Committee. He holds a J.D. from Yale Law School, where he served as an editor of the Yale Law Journal, and he has also earned Master's degrees in Public Administration and Arabic and Islamic Studies from Harvard University.